Waldomiro said:

&gt; I have an unit of code which show a message when any error happens.
&gt; Then the user needs to click ok to make the message disapears.
&gt; I&#39;d like to automatize the click, so the user doesn&#39;t need to 
&gt; be there when JUnit is testing my application.
&gt; Is there anyway to do that ?

Move the error message code into a factory method that you can override, for
example:

  public class SomeClass
  {
    public void doSomething()
    {
      if(!ok) { JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(...); }
    }
  }

To:

  public class SomeClass
  {
    public void doSomething()
    {
      if(!ok) { showWarning(); }
    }
    protected void showWarning()
    {
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(...);
    }
  }

Then within your test code:

  public void testDoSomething()
  {
    boolean [] warningShown[0] = { false };
    // override your message
    SomeClass c = new SomeClass()
    {
      protected void showWarning() 
      {
        warningShown[0] = true;
      }
    }
    // perform the work you want to test...
    c.doSomething();
    // check it
    assertTrue(warningShown[0]);
  }

I do similar things to this within some edit controls I&#39;ve written.  In real
life I want them to beep when something is wrong, in testing I don&#39;t.

Jonathan
